\deflang1033\pard\plain\f2\fs20 A NIGHT IN ELSINORE
\par 
\par                         a parody of William Shakespeare's       
\par                         HAMLET
\par                         committed by Richard Nathan
\par                          (Richard-Nathan@worldnet.att.net)
\par \tab \tab \tab \tab http://www.dramex.org/plays/scripts/elsinore.txt
\par ACT I
\par 
\par Scene I
\par 
\par 
\par Scene I takes place on a platform in front of 
\par Elsinore Castle.  FRANCISCO is on duty.  Enter 
\par BERNARDO.
\par 
\par 
\par         BERNARDO
\par Who's there?
\par 
\par         FRANCISCO
\par Nay, answer me.  Stand and unfold 
\par yourself.
\par 
\par         BERNARDO
\par Long live the King!
\par 
\par         FRANCISCO
\par Bernardo?
\par 
\par         BERNARDO
\par I am he.
\par 
\par         FRANCISCO
\par You come most carefully upon your 
\par hour.
\par 
\par         BERNARDO
\par 'Tis now struck twelve.
\par 
\par 
\par Off stage, there is the sound of someone 
\par approaching.
\par 
\par 
\par         FRANCISCO
\par Who is there?  Stand ho!
\par 
\par 
\par Enter HORATIO, who is dressed rather shabbily and 
\par who speaks with an unusual Italian accent.  He is 
\par more an antique Roman than a Dane.
\par 
\par 
\par         HORATIO
\par That's right!  You guessed it.
\par 
\par         BERNARDO
\par What's right?  Guessed what?
\par 
\par         HORATIO
\par You said, "Stand Ho!"  That's me!  
\par Ho!
\par 
\par         BERNARDO
\par Ho!  Ho who?
\par 
\par         HORATIO
\par Gezundheit!
\par 
\par         FRANCISCO
\par Why, 'tis good Horatio!  How dost 
\par thou, Horatio?
\par 
\par         HORATIO
\par I don't do much dusting anymore.  
\par I'm a guard now.  I guard the 
\par castle gate, and I do a pretty good 
\par job too.
\par 
\par         FRANCISCO
\par Really?
\par 
\par         HORATIO
\par Sure.  It's still there.
\par 
\par         BERNARDO
\par Has the apparition appeared again 
\par tonight?
\par 
\par         FRANCISCO
\par I have seen nothing.
\par 
\par         BERNARDO
\par Horatio, do you know ought of the 
\par Ghost?
\par 
\par         HORATIO
\par Well, I ought to.  Hey, that's some 
\par funny joke, eh?
\par 
\par         BERNARDO
\par Come, come, Horatio.  Do you know 
\par anything of ghosts?
\par 
\par         HORATIO
\par Sure, I knew an old ghost once.  
\par But that was a long, long time ago.  
\par He's probably dead by now.
\par 
\par         FRANCISCO
\par Look!  It comes again!  The ghost 
\par of our late King Hamlet!
\par 
\par 
\par Enter the GHOST, a bright-eyed imp who happens to 
\par be mute.
\par 
\par 
\par         BERNARDO
\par There is the apparition!
\par 
\par         HORATIO
\par I don't believe it.
\par 
\par 
\par The Ghost and Horatio joyously embrace.
\par 
\par 
\par         BERNARDO
\par Stay illusion!  If thou hast any 
\par sound or use of voice, speak to me!
\par 
\par 
\par The Ghost honks a horn.
\par 
\par 
\par         FRANCISCO
\par Question it, Horatio.
\par 
\par         HORATIO
\par Hey, Ghost, how ya doing?
\par 
\par 
\par The Ghost does a melodramatic death scene.
\par 
\par 
\par         HORATIO
\par You're dead, huh?  Gee, that's too 
\par bad.
\par 
\par 
\par The Ghost sits up and nods his head "yes."
\par 
\par 
\par         FRANCISCO
\par Ask him about the war!
\par 
\par         HORATIO
\par What war?
\par 
\par         FRANCISCO
\par Ask him if we should go to war with 
\par young Fortinbras!
\par 
\par         HORATIO
\par Hey, Ghost, should we go to war 
\par with Fortinbras?
\par 
\par 
\par The Ghost shakes his head "no."  He hold up ten 
\par fingers, and then three fingers.
\par 
\par 
\par         HORATIO
\par No.  He says Fortinbras is too 
\par many.  He thinks we should go to 
\par war with thirteen-bras.
\par 
\par 
\par The Ghost slaps his knee and goes into fits of 
\par silent laughter.
\par 
\par 
\par         FRANCISCO
\par No, no!  You remember, young 
\par Fortinbras is the son of old 
\par Fortinbras, who was King of Norway, 
\par until our late King Hamlet killed 
\par him and took most of the Norwegian 
\par lands.
\par 
\par 
\par The Ghost mocks Francisco's overly-serious manner, 
\par and makes faces at him.  Suddenly he looks 
\par offstage and panics.
\par 
\par 
\par         HORATIO
\par What's the matter?
\par 
\par 
\par The Ghost starts to run offstage, but Horatio 
\par blocks his way.
\par 
\par 
\par         HORATIO
\par Where you going?  What're you 
\par doing?
\par 
\par 
\par The Ghost whistles and points to the horizon.
\par 
\par 
\par         HORATIO
\par What do you mean?  I don't get it.
\par 
\par 
\par The Ghost decides to explain in pantomime.  The 
\par Ghost points down.
\par 
\par 
\par         HORATIO
\par Down?
\par 
\par 
\par The Ghost whistles and nods enthusiastically.  
\par Then the Ghost mimes picking up something and 
\par raising it.
\par 
\par 
\par         HORATIO
\par What?  Down is up?  You're crazy!  
\par How can down be up?
\par 
\par 
\par The Ghost shakes his head "no."  He holds out a 
\par hand to signal that he wants to start again.
\par 
\par 
\par         HORATIO
\par Okay.  We start again.
\par 
\par 
\par The Ghost mimes putting a cigar into his mouth, 
\par and then loping across the stage while raising and 
\par lowering his eyebrows.
\par 
\par 
\par         HORATIO
\par Wait a minute!  I think I seen that 
\par guy before.  Let me think ...  I 
\par know!  That's the man who comes to 
\par fix the sink!
\par 
\par 
\par The Ghost shakes his head "no."
\par 
\par 
\par         HORATIO
\par No?  Who is it?
\par 
\par 
\par The Ghost mimes holding a baby in his arms, acting 
\par like a father.
\par 
\par 
\par         HORATIO
\par It's your son?  It's Prince Hamlet?  
\par The one you named after yourself?  
\par Funny, he looks just like the man 
\par who comes to fix the sink.
\par 
\par 
\par The Ghost threatens to hit Horatio.
\par 
\par 
\par         HORATIO
\par OK.  Hamlet.   He's your son.  Your 
\par son!
\par 
\par 
\par The Ghost mimes proudly holding the baby in his 
\par arms.  Then he mimes lifting the baby up.
\par 
\par 
\par         HORATIO
\par He's going up?  Hamlet's going up?
\par 
\par 
\par The Ghost shakes his head "no," and then holds out 
\par his hand to signal that he wants to try again.
\par 
\par 
\par         HORATIO
\par OK.  We try again.
\par 
\par 
\par The Ghost again mimes Hamlet loping across the 
\par stage.  Then, as Hamlet, he starts silently 
\par weeping and crying.
\par 
\par 
\par         HORATIO
\par Hamlet.  He's sad.  He's crying.  
\par Why's he crying?
\par 
\par 
\par The Ghost points to himself and does his death 
\par scene again.  Then he goes back to Hamlet crying, 
\par and pointing to where he died.
\par 
\par 
\par         HORATIO
\par He cries because you're dead.  He's 
\par in mourning.
\par 
\par 
\par As soon as Horatio says, "mourning," the Ghost 
\par starts joyfully jumping up and down and nodding 
\par "yes."
\par 
\par 
\par         HORATIO
\par That's it!!!  Mourning!  It's 
\par morning ... 
\par 
\par 
\par The Ghost again mimes lifting the baby.
\par 
\par 
\par         HORATIO
\par . . .  and something's going up.  
\par The sun is coming up!  It's 
\par morning, dawn, and the sun is 
\par coming up, so you've got to leave 
\par now.  OK, I understand.  Good-bye, 
\par Ghost.  I'll be seeing you.  Good-
\par bye.
\par 
\par 
\par The Ghost exits, waving good-bye and blowing 
\par kisses.
\par 
\par 
\par         HORATIO
\par Hey, he's a nice ghost.
\par 
\par         FRANCISCO
\par Come.  Let us impart what we have 
\par seen tonight to young Prince 
\par Hamlet.
\par 
\par 
\par Exeunt.
\par 
\par 
\par 
\par **************************************************
\par 
\par 
\par Scene II
\par 
\par 
\par Scene II takes place in a room in Elsinore Castle.  
\par Flourish.  Enter the KING, the QUEEN, HAMLET (who 
\par has his back to the audience), POLONIUS, LAERTES, 
\par and OPHELIA.  The King is a slightly overweight 
\par man with a beard and a middle-European accent.  
\par His name is Claudius.  Gertrude, the Queen, is a 
\par stately dowager-type.  Polonius is a foolish old 
\par man.  Ophelia is an attractive blonde who is very 
\par clever and very ambitious.   Laertes is a young 
\par man, excitable, but not very bright.  In the 
\par original production of this play, he was played in 
\par a style resembling Daffy Duck (including the 
\par lisp), and it worked.
\par 
\par 
\par         KING
\par Though yet of Hamlet our dear 
\par brother's death the memory be 
\par green, and it befitted us to bear 
\par our hearts in grief, and our whole 
\par kingdom to be contracted in one 
\par brow of woe, it's time we faced the 
\par fact the old king's dead, and I 
\par must run the kingdom.  I thank you 
\par all for your condolences on the 
\par death of my brother, the late King, 
\par as I thank you for your good wishes 
\par on my marriage to his widow, the 
\par Queen.  Now then, on to our royal 
\par business.  Young Fortinbras has 
\par demanded that we surrender the 
\par lands lost by his father.  I have 
\par sent word to the aged king of 
\par Norway, ordering him to bring young 
\par Fortinbras into line!  Not one 
\par patch of land shall we give up!  
\par 
\par 
\par The King looks around the room.  Everyone except 
\par Hamlet looks pleased.  The King looks at Laertes.
\par 
\par 
\par         KING
\par Now, good Laertes, did you have 
\par something you wished to ask of me?
\par 
\par         LAERTES
\par Yes, Sire, your leave and favor to 
\par return to France.
\par 
\par         KING
\par Ahh, France, eh?  I'm told that 
\par France is a lovely country, and I 
\par hear they make most excellent wines 
\par there.  Go.  Enjoy yourself.  And 
\par be sure to send some postcards.  
\par Now, my nephew Hamlet, my son, how 
\par is it the clouds still hang on you?
\par 
\par 
\par Hamlet turns to face the audience, and we see his 
\par face for the first time.  Hamlet has a big, black 
\par mustache that looks as if it might have been 
\par painted on, and he smokes a cigar. 
\par 
\par 
\par         HAMLET
\par Nay, I am too much in the sun!  Get 
\par it? That's a joke.  My real father 
\par just died, and now I've got you for 
\par a father, so I'm too much in the 
\par sun!  Boy, that Shakespeare sure 
\par could write.  I'd like to see 
\par Francis Bacon pull off a joke like 
\par that.
\par 
\par         KING
\par Hmmmmm.  Come, Hamlet, my son, how 
\par is it the clouds still hang on you?
\par 
\par         HAMLET
\par I don't know.  Maybe it's because 
\par you're reigning.
\par 
\par         QUEEN
\par Good Hamlet, I know full well the 
\par love you bore your father.  But 
\par cast thy nighted color off!  If he 
\par were here today, do you think your 
\par father would want us to mourn on 
\par and on, wearing the same customary 
\par suit of solemn black, day in and 
\par day out?
\par 
\par         HAMLET
\par Well, he'd probably ask you to 
\par change your socks.
\par 
\par         QUEEN
\par Hamlet, . . .
\par 
\par         HAMLET
\par In fact, that's still a pretty good 
\par idea.  And while you're at it, 
\par change your husband.
\par 
\par         QUEEN
\par Hamlet, I loved your dear, departed 
\par father.  No woman could have loved 
\par him more.
\par 
\par         HAMLET
\par Of course not!  No other dame ever 
\par had a chance, not with you watching 
\par him like a hawk.  And a fat lot of 
\par good it did him,  ... poor old Dad.
\par 
\par         KING
\par Hamlet, it's unfortunate that your 
\par father died, but fathers have a way 
\par of doing that.  My father died, and 
\par his father died before him, and his 
\par father died...
\par 
\par         HAMLET
\par Yeah, but uncles go on forever.  
\par Don't you?
\par 
\par         KING
\par Hamlet, why don't you try to think 
\par of me as your father?
\par 
\par         HAMLET
\par OK, bury yourself six feet 
\par underground, and I'll give it a 
\par shot.
\par 
\par         KING
\par Gertrude, we must do something 
\par about this son of yours.
\par 
\par Exeunt all but Hamlet.
\par 
\par         HAMLET
\par Oh that this too, too solid flesh 
\par would melt, or at least that they 
\par would turn up the heat a little.  
\par To think that it should come to 
\par this!  My father but two months 
\par dead, and my mother married to this 
\par satyr.  I recall the day they wed.  
\par It was a satyr-day.  Heaven and 
\par Earth, must I remember?  My mother 
\par has married my uncle, and turned me 
\par into my own cousin.  Frailty, thy 
\par name is woman.  And woman, thy name 
\par is Frailty.  My name is Hamlet, and 
\par I'm ashamed to meet the both of 
\par you.
\par 
\par 
\par Enter Horatio, Francisco and Bernardo.  Horatio 
\par consults with his friends.
\par 
\par 
\par         HORATIO
\par Hey, is that him?
\par 
\par         HAMLET
\par Horatio, -- or I do forget myself!
\par 
\par         HORATIO
\par Well, I don't know.  Who do you 
\par think you are?
\par 
\par         HAMLET
\par I'm Hamlet, Prince of Denmark.
\par 
\par         HORATIO
\par Then you don't forget yourself... 
\par not unless you're the man who comes 
\par to fix the sink.  Then you got a 
\par problem.
\par 
\par         HAMLET
\par This can't be anyone but Horatio.  
\par Don't you remember me?  We went to 
\par school together!
\par 
\par         HORATIO
\par Sure, I know you!  You're Hamlet!
\par 
\par         HAMLET
\par And you're Horatio!  But I thought 
\par you were still going to school in 
\par Wittenberg.
\par 
\par         HORATIO
\par No, I left there a long time ago.  
\par I was too smart for them.
\par 
\par         HAMLET
\par Oh really?
\par 
\par         HORATIO
\par Yeah.  All the professors said 
\par they'd never be able to teach me 
\par anything.
\par 
\par         HAMLET
\par Horatio, something is rotten in the 
\par state of Denmark, and I think it's 
\par you.
\par 
\par         HORATIO
\par That reminds me.  I think I saw 
\par your father's ghost last night!
\par 
\par         HAMLET
\par What?  Are you sure it was him?  
\par Did you speak to him?
\par 
\par         HORATIO
\par We spoke.  But he wouldn't answer.
\par 
\par         HAMLET
\par That sounds like Dad, all right.  
\par Listen, boys, this is something I'm 
\par going to have to see for myself.  
\par Let's meet at the top of the castle 
\par tonight.
\par 
\par 
\par Exeunt.
\par 
\par 
\par 
\par **************************************************
\par 
\par 
\par Scene III
\par 
\par 
\par Scene III takes place in a room in Polonius' 
\par house.  Enter Laertes and Ophelia.
\par 
\par 
\par         LAERTES
\par My necessaries are embarked.  
\par Farewell.  And sister, do be wary 
\par of the affections of Prince Hamlet.  
\par Perhaps he does love you now, but 
\par he is subject to his birth, and 
\par therefore he must choose a royal 
\par bride.
\par 
\par         OPHELIA
\par Laertes, don't be such an ass!  Use 
\par your brain for once!  Do you think 
\par for one minute that Claudius is 
\par going to let Hamlet marry a 
\par princess?
\par 
\par         LAERTES
\par Huh?
\par 
\par         OPHELIA
\par Listen!  Hamlet has a better claim 
\par to the throne than his uncle 
\par Claudius does, right?  If Hamlet 
\par marries into another royal family, 
\par he'll gain powerful allies to help 
\par him win the crown.  You think 
\par Claudius wants that?  All I have to 
\par do is convince the King that 
\par Hamlet's been toying with my 
\par affections, and I guarantee you 
\par we'll be married before Hamlet 
\par knows what's hit him.  Then I'll 
\par figure out some way to get rid of 
\par Claudius, and I'll be Queen of 
\par Denmark!
\par 
\par         LAERTES
\par Sister, you're brilliant!  But 
\par look, here comes our father!
\par 
\par 
\par Enter Polonius.
\par 
\par 
\par         POLONIUS
\par Yet here, Laertes?  My blessings 
\par with thee!  And take these few 
\par precepts in thy memory:  Be thou 
\par familiar, but by no means vulgar.
\par 
\par 
\par Enter Horatio.
\par 
\par 
\par         HORATIO
\par What's he gonna do in France if he 
\par can't be vulgar?  How's he gonna 
\par fit in?
\par 
\par         POLONIUS
\par Horatio, you're not supposed to be 
\par here, are you?
\par 
\par         HORATIO
\par No, but I got two more hours before 
\par I'm supposed to go to a secret 
\par meeting with Hamlet at the top of 
\par the castle, so I got lots of time 
\par to kill.
\par 
\par         POLONIUS
\par I was just giving some advice to my 
\par son.
\par 
\par         HORATIO
\par That's OK.  I'll add vice too.  I 
\par got lots of vice.
\par 
\par         POLONIUS
\par Very well.  Laertes, neither a 
\par borrower nor a lender be . . .
\par 
\par         HORATIO
\par That's a good idea.  But you know 
\par what?  You're too late.  Laertes 
\par loaned me ten gold kroner this 
\par morning.
\par 
\par         POLONIUS
\par Then give it back to him!
\par 
\par         HORATIO
\par I can't.  Right after he gave me 
\par the money, I put it down, and then 
\par I lost it.
\par 
\par         POLONIUS
\par You put it down and lost it???
\par 
\par         HORATIO
\par Yeah, I put it down on a horse.
\par 
\par         POLONIUS
\par This is terrible.
\par 
\par         HORATIO
\par Yeah, now your son, he's a lender, 
\par and what are we gonna do?  Hey, I 
\par got a great idea!  You loan me ten 
\par gold kroner, and then I'll pay 
\par Laertes back, and then he won't be 
\par a lender anymore.
\par 
\par         POLONIUS
\par But if I lend you the money, then 
\par I'll be a lender, and you'll still 
\par be a borrower.
\par 
\par         HORATIO
\par OK, I got a better idea.  You don't 
\par be a lender, I don't be a borrower.  
\par You just give me the money.  How's 
\par that?
\par 
\par         POLONIUS
\par I don't know about this.
\par 
\par         HORATIO
\par You want your son to stay a lender 
\par all his life?
\par 
\par 
\par Polonius reaches into his money bag and takes out 
\par a gold coin.
\par 
\par 
\par         POLONIUS
\par But all I've got is this twenty-
\par kroner piece.  Have you got change 
\par for that?
\par 
\par         HORATIO
\par No, but I'll take it, just the 
\par same.
\par 
\par 
\par Horatio pockets the twenty-kroner piece.
\par 
\par 
\par         POLONIUS
\par At least you can now pay back to 
\par Laertes the ten kroner you owe him.
\par 
\par         HORATIO
\par Laertes, you got change for twenty 
\par kroner?
\par 
\par         LAERTES
\par No, I'm afraid not.
\par 
\par Horatio turns to Polonius.
\par 
\par         HORATIO
\par Now we got another problem.  I 
\par can't give this coin to him.  If I 
\par give him the coin, he'll owe me 
\par money.  If he owes me money, then 
\par he'll be a borrower.  He can't be a 
\par borrower if you just told him not 
\par to be a borrower!
\par 
\par         POLONIUS
\par But...
\par 
\par         HORATIO
\par Hey, I just got another great idea.  
\par Laertes, why don't you just say you 
\par gave me the ten gold kroner?  Then 
\par you won't be a lender!  You won't 
\par be a borrower!  You'll just be a 
\par nice guy, like your father!
\par 
\par         LAERTES
\par Sounds okay to me.
\par 
\par 
\par Ophelia, the only really smart one in the family, 
\par is furious with Horatio.  She scolds him, while 
\par Polonius and Laertes try to figure out what's been 
\par going on.
\par 
\par 
\par         OPHELIA
\par Horatio, you're nothing but a 
\par cheap, conniving crook!
\par 
\par         HORATIO
\par Yeah, that's me.
\par 
\par         OPHELIA
\par How can you be so dishonest?
\par 
\par         HORATIO
\par One time I tried to be honest, but 
\par then I said to myself, "Horatio, to 
\par thine own self be true."  So if 
\par mine own self is a crook, that's 
\par what I gotta do.  Good-bye!
\par 
\par 
\par Horatio walks out with his twenty-kroner piece.  
\par Ophelia glares at him.  Laertes and Polonius are 
\par still trying to puzzle out what happened to their 
\par money.  Exeunt Ophelia, Laertes and Polonius.
\par 
\par 
\par 
\par **************************************************
\par 
\par 
\par Scene IV
\par 
\par 
\par Scene IV takes place back on the platform in front 
\par of Elsinore Castle, where Scene I took place.  
\par Enter Hamlet, Horatio, Bernardo and Francisco.
\par 
\par 
\par         HAMLET
\par The air bites shrewdly; it is very 
\par cold.  Say, are you fellows sure 
\par this is where dear old Dad is going 
\par to show up?
\par 
\par         BERNARDO
\par The ghost has appeared at this very 
\par spot three nights past, my lord, 
\par then vanished before the sun came 
\par up.
\par 
\par 
\par We hear the distant pounding of a kettledrum, and 
\par a flourish of trumpets.
\par 
\par 
\par         FRANCISCO
\par What does this mean, my lord?
\par 
\par         HAMLET
\par That's the King.  He has the 
\par musicians play while he drinks.  He 
\par doesn't like to drink alone, so he 
\par has them play eight to the bar.  
\par You see, the King likes to take a 
\par drink before he goes to bed at 
\par night.  Then he likes to take a 
\par drink when he's in bed, especially 
\par if the Queen is still awake.  Then 
\par the Queen throws him out of bed, so 
\par he has to take another drink.  Then 
\par he's ready to throw the Queen out 
\par of bed, which calls for another 
\par drink.  Every time he takes a 
\par drink, he has the musicians bang 
\par the kettledrum.  As soon as the 
\par King is as tight as the drum, he 
\par knows it's time to fall asleep. 
\par 
\par         HORATIO
\par Hey, that sounds like a pretty good 
\par job.  You think I could be a king?
\par 
\par         HAMLET
\par Well, would you be willing to marry 
\par your brother's wife?  Do you think 
\par you could do that?
\par 
\par 
\par Horatio thinks this over.
\par 
\par 
\par         HORATIO
\par I don't know.
\par 
\par         HAMLET
\par Well, come on.  Do you want to be 
\par king, or don't you?
\par 
\par         HORATIO
\par If I marry the wife, do I get his 
\par mistress too?
\par 
\par         HAMLET
\par That's not strictly required.  It's 
\par not really part of the job.  But 
\par I'm sure we could work something 
\par out.
\par 
\par         HORATIO
\par Is she pretty?
\par 
\par         HAMLET
\par The wife or the mistress?
\par 
\par         HORATIO
\par Yes!
\par 
\par         HAMLET
\par You'll have to take that up with 
\par your brother.
\par 
\par         HORATIO
\par Hey, I just remembered!  I haven't 
\par got a brother!
\par 
\par         HAMLET
\par Then you'll have to take that up 
\par with your parents.  You do have 
\par parents, don't you?  Otherwise, 
\par you'll just have to take it up with 
\par your grandparents.
\par 
\par         HORATIO
\par I've got a great idea!  Why don't I 
\par just take your wife?
\par 
\par         HAMLET
\par My wife?  I'm not even married!
\par 
\par         HORATIO
\par That's all right.  I can wait.
\par 
\par         BERNARDO
\par Look my lord, it comes!
\par 
\par 
\par The Ghost enters, and is overjoyed to see Hamlet.  
\par The Ghost claps his hands and runs to embrace his 
\par son.
\par 
\par 
\par         HAMLET
\par Dad!
\par 
\par 
\par As the Ghost embraces Hamlet, the Ghost sticks his 
\par hands into the pockets of Hamlet's coat, pulls out 
\par an apple, and starts to eat it.
\par 
\par 
\par         HAMLET
\par Gee, it's nice to see you, Dad.
\par 
\par 
\par The Ghost nods happily, enjoying the apple.  Then 
\par the Ghost beckons Hamlet to follow him.  
\par 
\par 
\par         HAMLET
\par I think you boys better go.  I 
\par think he wants to be alone with his 
\par son.
\par 
\par         HORATIO
\par All right.
\par 
\par 
\par Exeunt Horatio, Bernardo and Francisco.  Again, 
\par the Ghost beckons Hamlet to follow him.
\par 
\par 
\par         HAMLET
\par OK, I'll follow you.
\par 
\par 
\par Exeunt the Ghost and Hamlet.
\par 
\par 
\par 
\par **************************************************
\par 
\par 
\par Scene V
\par 
\par 
\par Scene V takes place on another part of the 
\par platform.  Enter the Ghost and Hamlet.
\par 
\par 
\par         HAMLET
\par Where wilt thou lead me?  I'll go 
\par no further.
\par 
\par 
\par The Ghost shrugs, and stops.
\par 
\par 
\par         HAMLET
\par So, Dad, what's new?
\par 
\par 
\par The Ghost points to the apple core, grins, and 
\par gestures that he'd like something else to eat.
\par 
\par 
\par         HAMLET
\par I'm sorry, I don't have any more 
\par apples.
\par 
\par 
\par The Ghost makes a horrible disgusted face and 
\par turns away from Hamlet.
\par 
\par 
\par         HAMLET
\par Gee, if I'd only known, I...
\par 
\par 
\par The Ghost makes a disparaging wave of his arms at 
\par Hamlet, and makes another horrible face.
\par 
\par 
\par         HAMLET
\par Dad, isn't there something you 
\par wanted to tell me?
\par 
\par 
\par The Ghost suddenly remembers! He claps his hands 
\par and sits Hamlet down, and indicates that Hamlet 
\par should watch him.
\par 
\par 
\par         HAMLET
\par Oh.  OK.  You're going to tell me a 
\par story.
\par 
\par 
\par The Ghost nods his head happily.  Then he reaches 
\par into his coat and pulls out a little pillow.  He 
\par puts the pillow down on the floor and mimes going 
\par to sleep with his head on the pillow.  Hamlet 
\par waits for a minute, watching the Ghost sleep.
\par 
\par 
\par         HAMLET
\par Say, I thought Ghost stories were 
\par supposed to keep you awake.
\par 
\par 
\par The Ghost puts his fingers to his lips to indicate 
\par that Hamlet should be quiet, while he's sleeping.
\par 
\par 
\par         HAMLET
\par OK, you're sleeping.  Where are you 
\par sleeping?
\par 
\par 
\par The Ghost, still pretending to be asleep, holds up 
\par his hand, with the back of his hand facing the 
\par audience.  Then he pushes up the apple core to the 
\par top of his fingers, and mimes plucking an apple.
\par 
\par 
\par         HAMLET
\par Oh, you're asleep in the apple 
\par orchard.  I remember, you liked to 
\par sleep there!
\par 
\par 
\par The Ghost nods "yes."
\par 
\par 
\par         HAMLET
\par What happens next?
\par 
\par 
\par The Ghost stands up, takes the pillow and puts it 
\par under his shirt.  He pretends to be fat.  Then he 
\par pulls at an imaginary beard.
\par 
\par 
\par         HAMLET
\par A fat man...  a fat man with a 
\par beard...
\par 
\par 
\par The Ghost makes an ugly face and mimes yelling and 
\par being angry.
\par 
\par 
\par         HAMLET
\par A fat, nasty man with a beard!  
\par Your brother Claudius!
\par 
\par 
\par The Ghost nods "yes."  Then he goes back to 
\par putting on the nasty, evil face of Claudius.  He 
\par stomps around the stage, pulling on his beard.
\par 
\par 
\par         HAMLET
\par What does he do?
\par 
\par 
\par The Ghost, pretending to be Claudius, notices the 
\par apple core lying on the stage.  He picks it up, 
\par sees that it's been eaten, and brutishly throws it 
\par away.  He looks around the stage, and then looks 
\par in surprise at the spot where the Ghost was 
\par sleeping. The Ghost whips out the pillow, and 
\par resumes sleeping at that spot.
\par 
\par 
\par         HAMLET
\par OK, Claudius found you sleeping.  
\par What happened next?
\par 
\par 
\par The Ghost jumps up, puts the pillow back in under 
\par his shirt, and pretends to be Claudius.  He 
\par reaches into his coat, and pulls out a bottle of 
\par poison.  Then he reaches into his coat with his 
\par other hand and pulls out a funnel.  He walks over 
\par to where the Ghost has been sleeping, and mimes 
\par putting the funnel into the sleeping man's ear, 
\par and he pours the contents of the bottle into the 
\par funnel.  Then the Ghost whips out the pillow and 
\par becomes himself sleeping, with the funnel in his 
\par ear, and the poison being poured into it.  The 
\par Ghost wakes up and dies horribly.  
\par 
\par 
\par         HAMLET
\par Oh no!  Murder!  Foul and unnatural 
\par murder!  Claudius poured poison 
\par into your ear and killed you!!!  Oh 
\par murder most foul!!!
\par 
\par 
\par The Ghost sits up and nods his head in agreement.
\par 
\par 
\par         HAMLET
\par Oh horrible!  Oh, horrible, most 
\par horrible!  ...  Well, what do you 
\par want me to do about it?
\par 
\par 
\par The Ghost mimes hitting, kicking, choking, and 
\par jumping up and down on someone.
\par 
\par 
\par         HAMLET
\par You want me to take revenge on 
\par Claudius?
\par 
\par 
\par The Ghost nods "yes."
\par 
\par 
\par         HAMLET
\par Well, that sounds fair enough.  
\par What about Mom?
\par 
\par 
\par The Ghost shakes his head "no."  He reaches into 
\par his coat and takes out a poster-sized picture of 
\par the Queen.  He kisses the picture and looks coy.
\par 
\par 
\par         HAMLET
\par Not Mom.  You still love Mom.  Aww, 
\par that's sweet.  It's crazy, but it's 
\par sweet.  Maybe you should have your 
\par head examined, or at least your 
\par eyes.
\par 
\par 
\par The Ghost clutches the picture of the Queen to his 
\par chest, and looks threateningly at Hamlet.
\par 
\par 
\par         HAMLET
\par OK!  Don't worry.  I won't hurt 
\par Mom.  Just Claudius.
\par 
\par 
\par The Ghost shakes Hamlet's hand and pats him on the 
\par back.  Then the Ghost proceeds to put the picture, 
\par the pillow, the bottle and the funnel back into 
\par his coat.
\par 
\par 
\par         HAMLET
\par You have to go so soon?
\par 
\par 
\par The Ghost points to the horizon.
\par 
\par 
\par         HAMLET
\par Oh, I see.  The sun's coming up.  
\par OK, Dad. It was nice seeing you 
\par again.  I'll get your revenge for 
\par you.  You can count on me.
\par 
\par 
\par The Ghost waves good-bye and exits.
\par 
\par 
\par         HAMLET
\par Hmmmm.  Now what am I going to do?  
\par I can't just go downstairs and kill 
\par Claudius.  This is only Act I, and 
\par we've still got a whole play to 
\par fill up.  I know!  I'll pretend 
\par I've gone crazy.  That won't help 
\par me get revenge, but it should take 
\par up a few hours, and it may liven 
\par things up around here.
\par 
\par 
\par Enter Horatio, Bernardo, and Francisco.
\par 
\par 
\par         BERNARDO
\par Lord Hamlet!
\par 
\par         FRANCISCO
\par What news, my lord?
\par 
\par         HAMLET
\par Listen, boys, I don't want any of 
\par you to ever say a word about seeing 
\par that ghost, all right?
\par 
\par 
\par Off stage, the Ghost honks his horn.
\par 
\par 
\par         HAMLET
\par Swear!
\par 
\par         BERNARDO
\par Propose the oath, my lord, and we 
\par will swear it.
\par 
\par         HAMLET
\par Never to speak of what you have 
\par seen this night.
\par 
\par         FRANCISCO
\par But we haven't seen anything!  
\par 
\par         HAMLET
\par Then never to speak of what you 
\par haven't seen!
\par 
\par         HORATIO
\par I'm not sure I can remember 
\par everything I haven't seen.
\par 
\par 
\par Off stage, the Ghost honks his horn.
\par 
\par 
\par         HAMLET
\par Swear!  Swear that you'll remember 
\par to forget everything you haven't 
\par seen.
\par 
\par         HORATIO
\par I don't know.  I've got a pretty 
\par good memory.  
\par 
\par 
\par Hamlet gives each of then a gold kroner piece.
\par 
\par 
\par         HAMLET
\par Look, I'm going to lend each of you 
\par ten kroner.  Will you remember to 
\par pay back this loan?
\par 
\par         HORATIO
\par What loan?
\par 
\par         FRANCISCO
\par We have forgotten everything, my 
\par lord!
\par 
\par 
\par Off stage, the Ghost honks his horn.
\par 
\par 
\par         HAMLET
\par Swear!  Swear by my sword.
\par 
\par 
\par Hamlet isn't wearing a sword in this scene.  After 
\par this scene, he does wear a sword.
\par 
\par 
\par         HORATIO
\par You forgot to bring your sword!
\par 
\par         HAMLET
\par Then cross your hearts and hope to 
\par die!  
\par 
\par 
\par Off stage, the Ghost honks his horn.
\par 
\par 
\par         HAMLET
\par Swear!
\par 
\par         HORATIO, BERNARDO, & 
\par         FRANCISCO
\par We swear!
\par 
\par         HAMLET
\par So, gentlemen, let us go in 
\par together; and still your fingers on 
\par your lips, I pray.  The time is out 
\par of joint.  Oh cursed spite, that 
\par ever I was born to set it right!
\par 
\par 
\par Exeunt.
\par 
