\par 
\par ACT II
\par 
\par Scene I
\par 
\par 
\par Scene I of Act II takes place at Polonius's house.  
\par It's one month later.  Polonius enters.  A moment 
\par later, Ophelia runs in.
\par 
\par 
\par         POLONIUS
\par How now, Ophelia?  What's the 
\par matter?
\par 
\par         OPHELIA
\par Oh my lord, my lord, I have been so 
\par affrighted!
\par 
\par         POLONIUS
\par With what?
\par 
\par         OPHELIA
\par Have you noticed anything peculiar 
\par about Prince Hamlet recently?
\par 
\par         POLONIUS
\par Hamlet?  He's always been peculiar, 
\par ... but now that you mention it, he 
\par has been acting very strangely of 
\par late.  Why do you ask?
\par 
\par         OPHELIA
\par He came to my room just now.  He 
\par took me by the wrist and held me 
\par hard, then he fell to such perusal 
\par of my face as if he would draw it, 
\par and then he raised a sigh so 
\par piteous and profound, ...  I think 
\par he loves me.
\par 
\par         POLONIUS
\par This sounds like the very ecstasy 
\par of love!  Have you given him any 
\par hard words of late?
\par 
\par         OPHELIA
\par I've been refusing to see him, as 
\par you told me I must.  You ordered me 
\par to stay away from him because he 
\par would never be permitted to marry 
\par someone of my lowly station.
\par 
\par         POLONIUS
\par I was wrong!  He truly loves you, 
\par and your rejection has driven him 
\par mad!  In the morning we must go to 
\par the King.
\par 
\par 
\par Polonius exits.  Ophelia watches him go off.
\par 
\par 
\par         OPHELIA
\par My poor foolish father.  How easy 
\par it is to lead you from the truth.  
\par If the King as readily believes 
\par these lies of Hamlet's love, then 
\par soon shall I shall be Queen of 
\par Denmark!  
\par 
\par 
\par Ophelia exits after Polonius.   Enter Horatio with 
\par the Ghost of Hamlet's father.  They have been 
\par listening to the preceding scene.
\par 
\par 
\par         HORATIO
\par Hey Ghost, did you hear that?  It's 
\par a good thing we decided to spy.  
\par That lady's gonna make trouble for 
\par Hamlet.  I got to remember to warn 
\par him!
\par 
\par 
\par The Ghost nods in agreement.  Exeunt Horatio and 
\par the Ghost.
\par 
\par 
