\par 
\par Scene II
\par 
\par 
\par Scene II takes place in a room in the Castle.  
\par This room has an arras (a tapestry wall hanging.)  
\par Enter the King and Queen, followed by ROSENCRANTZ 
\par and GUILDENSTERN.  Rosencrantz is a portly fellow 
\par with a tiny mustache, who affects very polished 
\par manners.  Guildenstern is thin and speaks with an 
\par English accent. 
\par 
\par 
\par         KING
\par Welcome, dear Rosencrantz and 
\par Guildenstern. Moreover, that we 
\par much did long to see you, the need 
\par we have to use you did provoke our 
\par hasty sending.
\par 
\par         ROSENCRANTZ
\par Your Majesties!
\par 
\par 
\par Rosencrantz makes a very deep bow.  Guildenstern 
\par taps Rosencrantz on the shoulder and points to 
\par Claudius.
\par 
\par 
\par         GUILDENSTERN
\par Who's he?
\par 
\par         ROSENCRANTZ
\par That's the King!
\par 
\par         GUILDENSTERN
\par I thought you said the King was 
\par dead.
\par 
\par         ROSENCRANTZ
\par The old King is dead.  This is the 
\par new King!
\par 
\par 
\par Guildenstern looks at the King very carefully.
\par 
\par 
\par         GUILDENSTERN
\par He doesn't look very new to me.
\par 
\par 
\par Rosencrantz speaks to the King.
\par 
\par 
\par         ROSENCRANTZ
\par Please forgive my friend, your 
\par Majesty.  We've had a very long 
\par trip, and he's tired.
\par 
\par         GUILDENSTERN
\par No I'm not.  We had a nap after 
\par lunch...
\par 
\par 
\par Rosencrantz glares at Guildenstern, silencing him.
\par 
\par 
\par         KING
\par I trust that you have heard 
\par something of Prince Hamlet's 
\par transformation.  I don't know what 
\par may have caused this sudden change 
\par in him.  You are two of his oldest 
\par and dearest friends.  Perhaps you 
\par can tell us what is the matter.
\par 
\par         QUEEN
\par Good gentlemen, Hamlet has often 
\par talked of you.  I'm sure there 
\par aren't two men living of whom he is 
\par more fond.  Please stay with us 
\par awhile, and we will see that you 
\par are well rewarded.
\par 
\par         ROSENCRANTZ
\par It will be our pleasure to obey 
\par your every command, your Majesties.
\par 
\par         GUILDENSTERN
\par That's right!  After all, you are 
\par the King, even if you're not dead 
\par yet, so if there's anything we can 
\par do to make your job any easier, 
\par just call on us.
\par 
\par         ROSENCRANTZ
\par He means we're ready to do whatever 
\par you tell us.  The most difficult 
\par task won't be too difficult for us 
\par to attempt!  Isn't that right, 
\par Guildenstern?
\par 
\par         GUILDENSTERN
\par Yes, and the simplest task won't be 
\par simple enough for us to do either.  
\par What is it you want us to do, 
\par anyway?
\par 
\par         KING
\par Tell us what is wrong with Prince 
\par Hamlet!
\par 
\par 
\par Rosencrantz and Guildenstern confer privately in 
\par whispers, then Guildenstern speaks.
\par 
\par 
\par         GUILDENSTERN
\par We heard he's gone screwy.
\par 
\par         KING
\par We know that!  Find out why he's 
\par gone screwy!!!
\par 
\par         ROSENCRANTZ
\par We'll do our best, your Majesty.
\par 
\par         QUEEN
\par Go, and find Prince Hamlet!
\par 
\par 
\par Exeunt Rosencrantz and Guildenstern.  Enter 
\par Polonius.
\par 
\par 
\par         POLONIUS
\par My good lord, the ambassador from 
\par Norway has returned!
\par 
\par         KING
\par I trust he brings good news.
\par 
\par         POLONIUS
\par That reminds me, I think I have 
\par discovered the cause of Hamlet's 
\par lunacy.
\par 
\par         KING
\par Oh?  That is something I long to 
\par hear!
\par 
\par         POLONIUS
\par First listen to the ambassador.  My 
\par news shall be the fruit to that 
\par great feast.
\par 
\par         KING
\par Go then, and bring in the 
\par ambassador.
\par 
\par 
\par Polonius exits.  The King turns to the Queen.
\par 
\par 
\par         KING
\par Did you hear that?  Polonius thinks 
\par he has discovered the source of 
\par your son's strange behavior.
\par 
\par         QUEEN
\par I don't think it is anything but 
\par his father's death, and our own 
\par hasty marriage, but we shall see.
\par 
\par 
\par Re-enter Polonius with VOLTIMAND, the ambassador 
\par from Norway.
\par 
\par 
\par         KING
\par Well, what news from the King of 
\par Norway?
\par 
\par         VOLTIMAND
\par The King was very surprised by your 
\par letter.  He thought young 
\par Fortinbras was preparing to invade 
\par Poland, but when he found out that 
\par Fortinbras meant to attack Denmark, 
\par he rebuked him most severely.  
\par Young Fortinbras then promised the 
\par King he would never invade Denmark, 
\par but asked if he might invade Poland 
\par instead.  He would like your 
\par permission to bring his army 
\par through Denmark, on his way to 
\par attack the Poles.
\par 
\par         KING
\par Well, that sounds like a reasonable 
\par request.  Go back to Norway, and 
\par give young Fortinbras my permission 
\par to bring his army through Denmark.
\par 
\par 
\par Exit Voltimand.  The King turns to Polonius.
\par 
\par 
\par         KING
\par Now, Polonius, tell us your news!
\par 
\par         POLONIUS
\par I have a daughter.  She has told me 
\par that Hamlet has been sending her 
\par love letters.  I said to her, "Lord 
\par Hamlet is a prince, and above thy 
\par station!  Avoid him!"  She has 
\par avoided him, and since that time, 
\par he has gone mad!
\par 
\par         KING
\par Could this be true?
\par 
\par         QUEEN
\par It may be.
\par 
\par         POLONIUS
\par My daughter has given me an idea.  
\par Prince Hamlet often walks alone 
\par here in this part of the castle.  
\par Tomorrow my daughter will wait to 
\par meet him here.  We shall hide 
\par behind this arras, and see what 
\par happens then.
\par 
\par         KING
\par We will try it.
\par 
\par 
\par Enter Hamlet, reading a book.
\par 
\par 
\par         QUEEN
\par Look, how sadly the poor wretch 
\par comes reading.
\par 
\par         POLONIUS
\par Leave me to talk with him alone.
\par 
\par 
\par Exeunt the King and Queen.
\par 
\par 
\par         POLONIUS
\par How does my lord Hamlet?
\par 
\par         HAMLET
\par Booga-booga-booga!
\par 
\par         POLONIUS
\par Do you know me, my lord?
\par 
\par         HAMLET
\par Let's see, ...  Aren't you Abie the 
\par Fishman?
