\par Enter Rosencrantz and Guildenstern with the 
\par English EXECUTIONER.
\par 
\par 
\par         ROSENCRANTZ
\par Well, Guildenstern, here's another 
\par fine mess you've gotten me into.
\par 
\par 
\par Guildenstern starts weeping.  He tries to speak 
\par through his tears.
\par 
\par 
\par         GUILDENSTERN
\par But I didn't do anything!  I....
\par 
\par 
\par The English Executioner leads them off stage.
\par 
\par 
\par         HORATIO
\par Hey, who's that coming?
\par 
\par         HAMLET
\par Oh, that's just Osric, the 
\par courtier.
\par 
\par 
\par Enter OSRIC, a young courtier.
\par 
\par 
\par         OSRIC
\par Your lordship is welcome back to 
\par Denmark.  I bring word from the 
\par King.  He proposes to place a wager 
\par on a friendly, sporting duel 
\par between yourself and young Laertes.  
\par The King shall wager that in a 
\par dozen passes of the sword, Laertes 
\par shall not exceed you by three hits.
\par 
\par         HORATIO
\par Hey, that's good!  That sounds like 
\par fun.
\par 
\par         HAMLET
\par You think so?  All right, tell the 
\par King I'll do it, any time he's 
\par ready.
\par 
\par         OSRIC
\par I shall tell him, my lord.
\par 
\par 
\par Exit Osric.  Horatio also exits, and Hamlet calls 
\par out after him.
\par 
\par         HAMLET
\par Hey, where are you going?
\par 
\par         HORATIO
\par To place a bet against you.
\par 
\par 
\par Exit Horatio.
\par 
\par 
\par         HAMLET
\par It's nice to have the confidence of 
\par your friends.  There's something 
\par that bothers me about this duel.  
\par My stepfather, who's already tried 
\par to kill me once, has set up a 
\par fencing match with Laertes, who 
\par also hates me.  But Horatio seems 
\par to think the match is a good idea, 
\par which means I must be crazy to 
\par agree to it!  But what will come 
\par will come.  The readiness is all.  
\par And I don't think I'm ready yet!!!
\par 
\par 
\par Enter the King, Queen, Laertes, Osric and various 
\par other Courtiers and Attendants.  A moment later 
\par Horatio enters, having placed his bet.
\par 
\par         KING
\par Come, Hamlet, come and take this 
\par hand from me.
\par 
\par 
\par The King gives Laertes' hand to Hamlet.  They 
\par shake hands.
\par 
\par 
\par         HAMLET
\par Laertes, I want you to know that 
\par I'm sorry I killed your father and 
\par caused the death of your sister, 
\par but I'll forgive and forget if you 
\par will.
\par 
\par         LAERTES
\par (coldly)
\par I am satisfied.
\par 
\par         HAMLET
\par Then let's play the match.  Give us 
\par the foils.
\par 
\par         KING
\par Give them the foils, young Osric.
\par 
\par 
\par Osric brings Hamlet and Laertes two identical, 
\par bated fencing foils.  Laertes and Hamlet each take 
\par one.
\par 
\par 
\par         LAERTES
\par This is too heavy for me.  Let me 
\par see another.
\par 
\par 
\par Osric takes Laertes' foil, and goes off stage to 
\par get another one.
\par 
\par 
\par         HAMLET
\par This one seems OK.
\par 
\par 
\par Osric re-enters with a huge unbated sword for 
\par Laertes.  It is much larger than Hamlet's sword.  
\par Laertes takes the giant, deadly sword and takes a 
\par practice lunge.
\par 
\par 
\par         LAERTES
\par Yes, that's better.
\par 
\par         HAMLET
\par Say, are these weapons all of the 
\par same length?
\par 
\par         OSRIC
\par Of course, my lord.
\par 
\par         HAMLET
\par I just wanted to make sure mine 
\par wasn't longer.  I'd hate to have an 
\par unfair advantage.
\par 
\par         KING
\par Very well.  Let the match begin!
\par 
\par 
\par Hamlet and Laertes fence.  Hamlet is fairly fast 
\par and agile, and his footwork is unique.  He manages 
\par to avoid being hit by Laertes' sword.
\par 
\par 
\par         HAMLET
\par You know, Laertes, you should play 
\par Horatio sometime.  He's an expert 
\par on fencing.  He'll fence anything 
\par he can get his hands on.
\par 
\par 
\par Hamlet manages to hit Laertes.
\par 
\par 
\par         HAMLET
\par One!
\par 
\par         LAERTES
\par No.
\par 
\par         HAMLET
\par Judgment?
\par 
\par         OSRIC
\par A hit, a very palpable hit.
\par 
\par 
\par The King offers Hamlet the poisoned chalice of 
\par wine.
\par 
\par 
\par         KING
\par Congratulations, Hamlet.  Here is a 
\par chalice of wine for your 
\par refreshment.
\par 
\par         HAMLET
\par Nice try, Claudius, but it won't 
\par work.
\par 
\par         KING
\par What do you mean, Hamlet?
\par 
\par         HAMLET
\par I know what you're up to, trying to 
\par get me drunk!  I'm staying sober 
\par for this match!
\par 
\par 
\par Hamlet and Laertes fence.  Hamlet scores another 
\par hit.
\par 
\par 
\par         HAMLET
\par Another hit!  What say you?
\par 
\par         LAERTES
\par A touch, a touch, I do confess it.
\par 
\par 
\par The Queen takes the poisoned chalice.
\par 
\par 
\par         QUEEN
\par I drink to thy good fortune, 
\par Hamlet.
\par 
\par         KING
\par Gertrude, do not drink!
\par 
\par         QUEEN
\par I will, my lord; I pray you pardon 
\par me.
\par 
\par 
\par She drinks.  The King speaks quietly to himself.
\par 
\par 
\par         KING
\par It is the poisoned cup; it is too 
\par late.
\par 
\par         HAMLET
\par Come, Laertes.
\par 
\par 
\par They fence for a while, but no one is hit.  They 
\par pause.
\par 
\par 
\par         OSRIC
\par Nothing ether way.
\par 
\par         LAERTES
\par Have at you now!
\par 
\par 
\par Suddenly, Laertes stabs at Hamlet before the match 
\par has started again.  Hamlet is scratched by the 
\par envenomed sword.
\par 
\par 
\par         HAMLET
\par That was an unthrustworthy attack!
\par 
\par 
\par They start to fence again in earnest.  Laertes 
\par drops his sword.  Hamlet exchanges swords with 
\par him.  Hamlet wounds Laertes.  Suddenly, the Queen 
\par falls.
\par 
\par 
\par         OSRIC
\par Look to the Queen!
\par 
\par         KING
\par She swoons to see them bleed.
\par 
\par         QUEEN
\par No, no, the drink, the drink, -- 
\par Oh, my dear Hamlet, -- the drink, 
\par the drink --
\par 
\par 
\par Hamlet picks up the chalice and offers it to her.
\par 
\par 
\par         HAMLET
\par You want a drink?
\par 
\par         QUEEN
\par I am poisoned!
\par 
\par 
\par She dies.
\par 
\par 
\par         HAMLET
\par What???
\par 
\par 
\par Laertes falls.
\par 
\par 
\par         LAERTES
\par Hamlet, thou art slain.
\par 
\par         HAMLET
\par Don't be ridiculous!  This is a 
\par comedy!
\par 
\par         LAERTES
\par Thou art slain!  The treacherous 
\par instrument is in thy hand, unbated 
\par and envenomed.  Thy mother's 
\par poisoned.  The King, the King's to 
\par blame!
\par 
\par 
\par Hamlet is furious.  He turns to face Claudius.
\par 
\par 
\par         HAMLET
\par Thou incestuous, murderous, damned 
\par Dane, I'll kill you now!!!
\par 
\par 
\par However, before Hamlet can act, he starts thinking 
\par again.
\par 
\par 
\par         HAMLET
\par But which shall I use, the 
\par envenomed sword or the poisoned 
\par drink?  The sword would be more 
\par bloody and more certain, but it 
\par would seem too like an honorable 
\par soldier's death.  The poison is a 
\par more ignominious end, but there is 
\par little left, and how can I be sure 
\par he'd drink it down.  On the other 
\par hand, maybe I shouldn't kill him at 
\par all, now that his treachery is 
\par known to all, but let him live on 
\par in disgrace, until the people do 
\par ....
\par 
\par 
\par Everyone who is still alive yells at Hamlet.
\par 
\par 
\par         ALL
\par Kill him already!  Make up your 
\par mind and kill him!!!
\par 
\par         HAMLET
\par Oh, what the hell!
\par 
\par 
\par Hamlet stabs Claudius with the envenomed sword, 
\par and at the same time pours the poisoned drink down 
\par his throat.  Claudius dies.
\par 
\par 
\par         LAERTES
\par He is justly served.  Exchange 
\par forgiveness with me, noble Hamlet!  
\par I blame you not for mine and my 
\par father's death.  Blame me not for 
\par thine!
\par 
\par 
\par Laertes dies.  Hamlet collapses, and Horatio goes 
\par to him.
\par 
\par 
\par         HAMLET
\par I am dying, Horatio.  I'd always 
\par hoped the ending would be funnier 
\par than this.
\par 
\par         HORATIO
\par You want me to tell some jokes?
\par 
\par         HAMLET
\par I didn't think I'd die, as long as 
\par I kept this a comedy.  Maybe 
\par killing Rosencrantz and 
\par Guildenstern wasn't such a funny 
\par idea after all.  Horatio, how is it 
\par that you're the only major 
\par character to survive?  The only one 
\par in the entire play?
\par 
\par         HORATIO
\par It's funny you should ask.  I 
\par didn't think I was gonna live.  In 
\par fact, I was so sure I was gonna 
\par die, I bet this guy named Will 
\par Shakespeare 200 kroner that I'd die 
\par before the play was over, and what 
\par do you think happens?  I lose the 
\par bet!  Just my luck, huh?
\par 
\par         HAMLET
\par The rest is silence.
\par 
\par 
\par Hamlet dies.  The sound of military drums comes 
\par from off stage.
\par 
\par 
\par         HORATIO
\par Hey, what's that noise?
\par 
\par 
\par Osric runs off stage to find out.  He returns.
\par 
\par 
\par         OSRIC
\par Young Fortinbras, with conquest 
\par comes from Poland.
\par 
\par 
\par Enter YOUNG FORTINBRAS and some of his soldiers.  
\par Young Fortinbras has a ski-slope shaped nose, and 
\par speaks with rapid-fire delivery.
\par 
\par 
\par         FORTINBRAS
\par Hi, this is Young "Happy To Be Back In Denmark" 
\par Fortinbras, and I gotta tell you, I thought I'd 
\par seen bloodshed in Poland, but this is ridiculous.  
\par I was going to give the Danish court a twenty-one 
\par gun salute, but it looks like someone beat me to 
\par it.  You know, a funny thing happened on the way 
\par to the castle.  I ran into the English Ambassador, 
\par and he told me that Rosencrantz and Guildenstern 
\par are dead.  I said, "Who isn't?"  But I love 
\par Elsinore, it's gotta be the only place on Earth
\par where they built a moat to protect the people 
\par outside from the violence inside the castle.  But 
\par seriously, folks, such a sight as this becomes the 
\par field, but here shows much amiss.  Go bid the 
\par soldiers shoot.  
\par 
\par 
\par Exeunt, bearing off the dead bodies; after which a 
\par peal of ordinance is shot off.
\par 
